The paper proposes a framework for semi-supervised clustering, which is a common topic in machine learning and data mining. The use of active learning and interaction with a domain expert suggests a focus on artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG). The study of query and computational complexity suggests a focus on algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). The use of clustering and margin-based methods suggests a focus on natural language processing (cs.CL) and computer vision (cs.CV).
